= Introduction

Civilization in EVE Frontier does not emerge from individuals. It emerges from the coordination of groups.

Tribes, syndicates, and alliances form the social layer of the game world. Yet there is a contradiction: the game gives players powerful programmable primitives --- Smart Assemblies --- meant to drive player-run gameplay, but players have no way to use them together.

Groups rely on Discord channels and shared spreadsheets to manage operations that involve real on-chain assets. Trust is social, ownership is individual, delegation is nonexistent.

When leaders leave or groups break apart, disputes cannot be resolved. Who contributed what, and what they are owed, is never recorded and never enforced.

These are not minor problems. They are the reason a player economy has not emerged.

== The Assembly Paradox

Smart Assemblies are composable, programmable, and powerful.

A single gate assembly can control trade routes. A network of storage assemblies can form a logistics chain. A fleet of mining assemblies can extract resources at industrial scale.

The building blocks exist for players to build empires. Yet their usage stays small.

The problem is not what the technology can do. It is what players can organize.

Consider what it takes to run a gate network:

- Someone must fund the initial deployment.
- Someone must set toll rates and access rules.
- Revenue must be collected and split fairly.
- Maintenance decisions must be made as a group.
- If the operator disappears, the infrastructure must survive.

Each of these needs an organizational layer that does not exist on-chain.

Players who have built DApp products using assemblies have seen the same pattern. The products work, but people do not use them --- not because they are not useful, but because they do not feel _natural_.

People try them out of curiosity or to support the builders. Not because the products fit into how they already play.

== The Missing Layer

Building applications on top of assemblies is necessary but not enough.

What we learned is simple: players will not use tools that feel separate from the game. They need tools that fit how they already organize --- tools that solve problems they already have.

What players are missing:

- *Trust infrastructure* --- a way to define who can do what and enforce it, without relying on personal trust.
- *Shared ownership* --- assets that belong to the group, not to one person's wallet.
- *Delegation* --- the ability to create teams and departments with clear, limited authority.
- *Value capture* --- a way to track contribution, share revenue, and fund group projects from a common pool.

These needs are the same across every tribe, syndicate, and alliance in Frontier.

They are what a player economy requires to exist. They must be solved at the protocol level --- not inside individual applications, but as a shared foundation that every group can build on.
